  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3410341816" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3410341816" />
    <a title="Greg" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/2855874-greg"><img alt="Greg" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1500902430p2/2855874.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3410341816?book_show_action=true">Jun 27, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Greg" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Greg" href="/user/show/2855874-greg">Greg</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="did not like it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">did not like it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3410341816" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer4703763353220059720">I thought I would get more out of this read than I did based on the strong recommendations. Instead, what I received was the same load of absurdity that spews fourth daily from the social justice hivemind. I was unable to find a logical argument or sensible course of action from this text.<br/><br/>How do you know if something is about race? Oluo&apos;s answer: It is about race if a person of color thinks it&apos;s about race.<br/><br/>So she shuts down any sensible discussion right from chapter 1. <i>Nice</i>.<br/><br/>Even Oluo&apos;s own mothe</span>
  <span id="freeText4703763353220059720" style="display:none">I thought I would get more out of this read than I did based on the strong recommendations. Instead, what I received was the same load of absurdity that spews fourth daily from the social justice hivemind. I was unable to find a logical argument or sensible course of action from this text.<br /><br />How do you know if something is about race? Oluo's answer: It is about race if a person of color thinks it's about race.<br /><br />So she shuts down any sensible discussion right from chapter 1. <i>Nice</i>.<br /><br />Even Oluo's own mother isn't safe from this tirade. She labels her a racist and goes on to complain about her white mother and how she always wants to talk about race. What on earth is Ijeoma doing in this book if not talking about race?<br /><br />She wastes an entire chapter talking about how people want to touch her hair. Is this seriously the level of tragedy we're addressing? A claim that came particularly close to me is her assertion that haircut standards in the military are racist. <i>Excuse me?</i> I served with hundreds of black Marines and soldiers. Four out of the last six Sergeants Major of the Marine Corps were black, and they are the most aggressive enforcers of hair cut standards in the world. I have <i>never</i> heard of anyone taking issue with the Marine Corps grooming standards. Go to the base barber and tell them you want a medium reg. They don't give a shit what color you are. You'll come out of there with a haircut Sergeant Major would approve of.<br /><br />Her chapter on cultural appropriation is wrought with even more frustrating white blaming. She expresses her frustration at the lack of authentic African restaurants in this country. Nearly every one of the problems she mentions has been solved by Asian and Latino immigrants opening successful restaurants. Why are they successful? Why aren't African-Americans opening more restaurants? Did she consider that most African-Americans have never been to Africa and the color of their skin doesn't grant them profound knowledge of African food any more than my eyes qualify me to cook Chinese food? Could it be that African-Americans are just Americans?<br /><br />She goes on to claim that the white man stole black music (rap), and a white person only needs half the talent of a black person to go multi-platinum. Just because he's white. Has she been living under a rock for the last 40 years? Take a quick look at the best selling rappers of all time, and it's obvious that other than Eminem, black rappers absolute <i>dominate</i> the genre. Only about 3 of the top 50 rappers of all time are <i>not</i> black.<br /><br />This book absolutely fails to bring up substantiated, logical, or original arguments that support the claims and accusations constantly thrown around in today's racially charged social world. Instead, she spits an emotionally charged and ridiculous pile of word vomit.<br /><br />If you want a read that actually provides hard evidence and substantiated claims on racial issues in the United States, I recommend picking up <i>The Color of Law</i>.<br /><br />If you'd like to engage in quality discussions with other people with different viewpoints rather than the divisive and insensitive babble in this book, I recommend looking at <i>We Need to Talk: How to Have Conversations that Matter</i>.<br /><br />Unless you are devoid of critical thinking ability and prefer a mob to think for you, I would recommend passing on this book.</span>
  <a data-text-id="4703763353220059720" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


