  <div class="xhr_comment_body">
    <a style="font-weight:bold" href="/user/show/134951931-grace">Grace</a>

      
<span id="freeTextContainer13724126709078990910">If you’re white then it’s true, you don’t get it. How could you if you’ve never actually experienced it? Have you ever had to worry about your kid get</span>
  <span id="freeText13724126709078990910" style="display:none">If you’re white then it’s true, you don’t get it. How could you if you’ve never actually experienced it? Have you ever had to worry about your kid getting killed by cops for doing nothing wrong? Have you ever been followed around stores for no reason other then the way you look? Have you ever lost a job interview just because of the color of your skin? No, you haven’t. Because you’re white. Check your privilege. Unless you have the power to magically turn into a POC then yeah, you’ll never actually completely understand what POC are going through. The whole point of the book was to talk about race. It’s literally called So You Want to Talk About Race. All the author meant was that your opinion doesn’t define the conversation because you aren’t the one negatively effected by the problem. I’m also white and I have always had very very curly hair. Curly hair is part of Black culture. It’s not part of white culture. Most white people have straight hair. It’s a fact. Deal with it and the fact that this isn’t about you. At all. Don’t get defensive over silly things that are NOT about you personally. And about your forth paragraph… if you had actually read the book like you claim to then you would know about systemic racism. Have you ever heard about implicit biases? You should look it up. Check out the Harvard Implicit Bias Project. Maybe then you’ll realize how ignorant, racist, and absolutely wrong you are.</span>
